pr_title: sse4.2: added the implementation for mm_cmpestra
pr_body:
sse4.2: added the implementation for mm_cmpestra

I have created this PR from a new branch as old branch's commit history became very messy.
The implementation is same as old branch.
I am trying to add tests in such a way that each block(case) of code is tested for 2 different values of imm8 and also for both size=8 and size=16 variants.
So for cmpestra there would be 14 cases as written in a comment in the tests file.
I have named the test cases functions to indicate which block of code they would be surely testing.
I have only implemented 4/14 for now, I will implement the rest after getting feedback.
I can also merge different cases in one big test function but I think it looks cleaner this way, if anything needs to be changed please inform me.
Thank You
PS: I am using generator code :)
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 426149276, 'comment_body': 'Either the native aliases script needs to not match on trailing `[A-Za-z0-9_]` or this function could be renamed `simde_x_mm_cmpestra_8_` to avoid the issue', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 16, 12, 27, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mr-c', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426172905, 'comment_body': "The former I think.  I'll take a look at the native aliases renamer.

Meanwhile, I think a better solution would be to use `simde_mm_cmpestra()` in the tests; it's the public API we're interested in testing anyways.  They can still be in test separate functions, _mm_cmpestra will delegate to the right function based on imm8.

The trailing _ indicates that it's a private API; _x is for public SIMDe extensions, so I think the name should stay.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 16, 17, 23, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nemequ', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426173609, 'comment_body': 'You can just do

```c
case SIMDE_SIDD_CMP_EQUAL_ANY:
case SIMDE_SIDD_CMP_RANGES:
  bitvalue = 0;
  break;
```

Sorry I missed this in the last round :(', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 16, 17, 33, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nemequ', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426228786, 'comment_body': 'I found the bug, cmp_op should be 0x0c instead of 0x06.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 7, 37, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'masterchef2209', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428336388, 'comment_body': '@nemequ what should I do here, if I have to use 2 operators inside this loop?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 20, 22, 9, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'masterchef2209', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428358634, 'comment_body': "You can't have two reductions on the same variable.

That said, I don't see why you need this; `int_res_1` is initialized to 0 (all bits unset), so you shouldn't need to unset the bits here.  You only need to handle the case where the bits should be set but aren't.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 20, 23, 11, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nemequ', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428545154, 'comment_body': 'Seems that `SIMDE_BUG_CLANG_45959` is not used in this PR?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 9, 28, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mr-c', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428612457, 'comment_body': '        `HEDLEY_DIAGNOSTIC_PUSH

        HEDLEY_DIAGNOSTIC_POP`
It is used in this part of code(Line 171), is something wrong here?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 21, 12, 8, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'masterchef2209', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 428645107, 'comment_body': "my mistake!
